Themes can add to app.locals through app-locals.json in their root dir.

In particular, this allows themes to override APP_NAME, which is
what the CSOL theme now does.

Made the app name an app local var, rather than hardcoding it to Aestimia.

This will allow us to make the app name customizeable.
rename dot_min app local var to DOT_MIN, as it's a constant.

Implemented a theme system that allows for custom HTML/CSS/JS content.

Themes are directories that contain `static` and `views` directories.
The `static` directory is mounted at `/theme/`, and any templates in the
`views` directory override Aestimia's standard templates. The primary
one to override is `layout.html`, which should extend `base-layout.html`.
This file can define its own `theme_head` and `theme_footer` blocks;
we can always add more blocks to `base-layout.html` if we need to make
it possible for themes to override other parts of pages.

I haven't yet documented this fully in README.md, because I wanted to
try out the system for a bit before investing too much into it, but
it seems decent and extensible enough.

Revert "Different themes can be specified via CSS_THEME_URL env var."

This reverts commit e18eb423d963c1178da0934f28b3379489dbd478.

Reverting because we'll need plenty more ways to customize than just
CSS overrides, as CSOL needs a completely custom footer. There's
probably a more extensible solution that involves specifying a different
Jinja template rather than a separate style sheet.

Different themes can be specified via CSS_THEME_URL env var.

The default theme is now pure Bootstrap.

Also switched the nav list items to be styled via pseudo-selectors instead
of manual even/odd/first/last classes, as the latter is hard to maintain
and the styling isn't critical--if a browser doesn't support the
pseudo-selectors, no functionality is lost.
minor fixes to make login/logout smoother.

Added 'mediaType' field to submission evidence schema.

Currently there are only two media types, 'image' and 'link', with
the default being 'link'. The submission detail template simply links
out to links, while it presents a thumbnail of images. Adding more
media types isn't hard.

Right now I'm assuming that clients will ask for submission status on a
per-learner basis, e.g. whenever a learner logs in. If we need something
else, we can add additional search criteria later.

Mentors must now assign submissions to themselves before assessing.

They have 15 minutes to assess a submission by default, at which point
someone else can assess it.

Note that this is not intended as a security mechanism, as it's technically
still possible for a properly-formed POST request to add a review to
the assessment; this is simply done as an aid to avoid race conditions.
